# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: a1-motorway-netherlands
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a1-motorway-netherlands] The **A1** is a motorway in the Netherlands.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a1-motorway-netherlands] The road connects the capital city of Amsterdam, near the interchange of Watergraafsmeer, with the German border, near Oldenzaal and Bad Bentheim, and the German Autobahn BAB 30.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a1-motorway-netherlands] On its way, it crosses four provinces: North Holland, Utrecht, Gelderland and Overijssel.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a1-motorway-netherlands] The section of the road between its start at the interchange Watergraafsmeer, and the interchange of Hoevelaken near Amersfoort, is also a European route: the E231.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a1-motorway-netherlands] This section of the A1 is the complete E231 route; the E231 does not consist of any other road or section.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a1-motorway-netherlands] Between the interchange Hoevelaken and the German border (and beyond, along the BAB 30), the European route E30 follows the A1 motorway.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a1-motorway-netherlands] This European route is a so-called A-Class West-East European route, going from Cork in Ireland all the way to Omsk in Russia.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] The **A10 motorway** (Dutch: *Rijksweg 10*) is a motorway in the Netherlands.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] This motorway is the ring road around the city of Amsterdam.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] Five other motorways connect to the A10: motorway A8 at interchange Coenplein (north), motorway A5 at interchange Coenplein (south), A4 at interchange De Nieuwe Meer, A2 at interchange Amstel, and A1 at interchange Watergraafsmeer.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] Part of the A10 is the Coentunnel, crossing the Noordzeekanaal ("North Sea Canal").
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] This twin tube tunnel was notorious for traffic jams for decades and another two tubes have been built.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] These new tubes opened on 13 May 2013 and the old tubes were closed for extensive renovation.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] On 21 July 2014 the old tubes were reopened after completing the renovations and all four tubes became be available for traffic.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] The city of Amsterdam has a network of numbered *stadsroutes* (city routes).
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] These routes are indicated with an "s" prefix followed by a three digit number starting at 100.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] Since these s-routes are connected to the A10 motorway and each s-route only crosses the motorway once, these numbers can be considered as the first exit numbers on Dutch motorways.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] Recently, regular exit numbering has been implemented based on the numbers of the s-routes.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] For example, the junction leading towards the s106 used to be exit number s106 and is now numbered as exit 6.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] Construction started in 1962, and the first part was completed four years later.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] The Coentunnel was opened on 21 June 1966.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] The western part of the A10 (the *Einsteinweg*) was finished on 2 April 1975 and the southern part on 7 July 1981.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] The eastern and northern part were finished in 1990, with the completion of another tunnel under the IJ, the Zeeburgertunnel.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] The western part of the A10, between interchange De Nieuwe Meer with the A4 and exit 2, has a speed limit of 80 km/h (50 mph).
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] The rest of the A10 is 100 km/h (62 mph).
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] During rush hour the speed on the southern part can be reduced to 80 km/h if the hard shoulder is opened for use as an additional traffic lane.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] The entire route is in North Holland Province.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a10-motorway-netherlands] The A10 south between the De Nieuwe Meer junction and the Amsterdam-Buitenveldert connection is being converted into a tunnel as part of the Zuidasdok project, in order to expand Amsterdam Zuid station and Amsterdam RAI station.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a12-motorway-netherlands] The **A12 motorway** is a motorway in the Netherlands.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a12-motorway-netherlands] The road connects the city of The Hague with the German border, near Zevenaar, and the German Autobahn BAB 3.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a12-motorway-netherlands] On its way, it crosses three Dutch provinces: South Holland, Utrecht, and Gelderland.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a12-motorway-netherlands] The section of the A12 road within the city of The Hague (near exits 1, 2 and 3) is actually not a motorway, but a highway.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a12-motorway-netherlands] This part of the road, known as the *Utrechtsebaan*, is too narrow to meet the Dutch requirements for a motorway (for example, it does not have a shoulder), and is therefore a highway with a maximum speed of 70 km/h.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a12-motorway-netherlands] To block local traffic from using this heavily congested part of the road, exits 2 through 4 are built as incomplete exits.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a12-motorway-netherlands] These exits only feature westbound exits and eastbound entrances, so they can only be used by interlocal traffic.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a12-motorway-netherlands] Local traffic is therefore forced to make use of the available local roads.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a12-motorway-netherlands] In 2008, a government programme on route branding, under an umbrella project in urban planning, put stickers on all streetlights of the A12, citing efforts to give it a "route 66-like" allure.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a12-motorway-netherlands] This plan, dubbed the "regenboogroute" (*rainbow route*), received news coverage because of its alleged trivial results (stickers on streetlights) and high costs (€120 000).
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a12-motorway-netherlands] The Utrechtsebaan has been the location of numerous blockades by the climate group Extinction Rebellion.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a12-motorway-netherlands] With daily blockades taking places since 9 September 2023.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a12-motorway-netherlands] They block the road to demand the end of fossil subsidies.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a13-motorway-netherlands] The **A13 motorway** is a motorway in the Netherlands, connecting the cities of The Hague and Rotterdam.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a13-motorway-netherlands] The Rotterdam The Hague Airport is located next to the A13.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a13-motorway-netherlands] The 17-kilometre-long (11 mi), highly congested motorway is the main motorway connection between these two cities.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a13-motorway-netherlands] It is a dual carriageway with three lanes in each direction.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a13-motorway-netherlands] Between the junctions Berkel and Delft-Zuid managed motorway is effective, when certain intensities occur the hard shoulder is opened for traffic heading north.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a13-motorway-netherlands] The maximum speed on the road is 100 km/h.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a13-motorway-netherlands] European route E19, the route between Amsterdam and Paris, follows the complete A13 motorway between the interchanges Ypenburg and Kleinpolderplein.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a13-motorway-netherlands] To relieve the southern part of A13 motorway from traffic, a major by-pass for the city of Rotterdam was constructed, connecting the A13 directly with the A16 motorway.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a13-motorway-netherlands] The A16 was extended from its former terminus at interchange Terbregseplein towards a new interchange with the A13 between exits Berkel en Rodenrijs and Delft-Zuid.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a13-motorway-netherlands] This extension was completed in October 2025.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a13-motorway-netherlands] The remaining part of the A13, between this interchange and interchange Ypenburg, would then have to be widened.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a13-motorway-netherlands] The entire route is in South Holland Province.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a15-motorway-netherlands] The Dutch **A15 motorway** (**Rijksweg 15**) is a motorway in the Netherlands, the **A18** used to make part of it until may 2024.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a15-motorway-netherlands] In governmental plans, the A15 and A18 together were meant to be one long motorway from the Europoort harbor near Rotterdam towards the town of Varsseveld in the east of the country.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a15-motorway-netherlands] However, the section between the interchange Ressen at Lingewaard near Nijmegen and Zevenaar was not completed.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a15-motorway-netherlands] To avoid confusion for drivers, the eastern part of the road has been given a different number: A18.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a15-motorway-netherlands] Construction of the extension began in 2019 and was planned for completion between 2021 and 2023.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a15-motorway-netherlands] It is unclear whether the A18 route will be renumbered as the A15 once the connection to the A12 is made.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a15-motorway-netherlands] The westernmost part of the road, between the Maasvlakte and exit 8 is officially not an *Autosnelweg* (motorway), and is therefore known as the N15.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a15-motorway-netherlands] However, it has most characteristics of a motorway, such as a central barrier and a hard shoulder until it crosses the Coloradoweg on the Maasvlakte.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a15-motorway-netherlands] As of exit 8, the road becomes an official motorway, called A15.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a15-motorway-netherlands] Together with the Betuweroute, which runs parallel on several stretches, the A15 is a main transport corridor from the Port of Rotterdam to the east.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a15-motorway-netherlands] In 2010, the A15 motorway near Rotterdam has been widened between the exit Brielle and the interchange Vaanplein.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a15-motorway-netherlands] To the western part, between Brielle and Spijkenisse, one lane in each direction will be added, making it a 2x3 road.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a15-motorway-netherlands] As for the eastern part of the section, between Spijkenisse and the Vaanplein, the current 2x3 road has been upgraded to a 2x5 road.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a15-motorway-netherlands] The complex project in this highly industrialized part of Rotterdam caused an extensive loss of €103 million to one of the main contractors of the project, Ballast Nedam, in the year 2014.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a16-motorway-netherlands] The **A16 motorway** is a motorway in the Netherlands.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a16-motorway-netherlands] It runs from the Interchange Zestienhoven in the northwestern part of Rotterdam, towards the Belgian border near Hazeldonk.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a16-motorway-netherlands] The motorway has 22 exits including 8 interchanges.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a16-motorway-netherlands] To relieve the southern part of A13 motorway from traffic, a major by-pass for the city of Rotterdam was constructed, extending the A16 was extended from its former terminus at interchange Terbregseplein towards a new interchange with the A13 between exits Berkel en Rodenrijs and Delft-Zuid.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a16-motorway-netherlands] Nearly the entire A16 motorway, including both the local and express lanes near Rotterdam, featured a maximum speed of 100 km/h.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a16-motorway-netherlands] The only exception to this were two short sections: between Dordrecht and Klaverpolder as well as the section between the intersection Princeville, west of Breda and the Belgian border, where a speed of 120 km/h is allowed.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a16-motorway-netherlands] At the section between the Moerdijk bridges and the Belgian border the maximum speed changed to 130 km/h as of 2011.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a16-motorway-netherlands] Near Rotterdam, a system of collector–express lanes is used.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a16-motorway-netherlands] The exits 24 through 26 are only accessible through the outer (collector) lanes.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a16-motorway-netherlands] The inner lanes serve as express lanes and do not have any exits.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a16-motorway-netherlands] In the northern direction, there are three express lanes of which one lane is reserved for buses and trucks, while on the southbound express lanes three regular lanes are available, of which none is reserved for special vehicles.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a16-motorway-netherlands] On two sections of the road, other Dutch motorways run along the north–south motorway A16.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a16-motorway-netherlands] Between interchanges Klaverpolder and Zonzeel, the east–west A59 motorway follows the route of the A16 for about 8 kilometers.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a16-motorway-netherlands] Further south, between interchanges Princeville and Galder, the same goes for the (also east–west) A58 motorway, for a distance of about 6 kilometers.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a16-motorway-netherlands] Besides, European route E19 (Amsterdam–Paris) follows the complete route of the A16 motorway between the Terbregseplein in Rotterdam and the Belgian border near Breda.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a17-motorway-netherlands] The **A17 motorway** is a motorway in the Netherlands.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a17-motorway-netherlands] It runs from the interchange Klaverpolder, just south of the Moerdijk bridge in the A16 motorway, towards the interchange De Stok with the A58 motorway, near Roosendaal.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a17-motorway-netherlands] The A17 motorway is 25 kilometers long, and serves as an alternative route between the cities of Rotterdam and Antwerp, especially towards the latter's harbor, which is located in the western part of the city.
[src:a1-motorway-netherlands/a17-motorway-netherlands] The entire route is in North Brabant Province.
